Document: Compute Shaders
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/compute_shaders.rst
Summary: This section introduces compute shaders in Godot, explaining their purpose, structure, and basic GLSL syntax for a minimal example.

A compute shader is a versatile shader program designed for general-purpose computation, offering more flexibility than traditional vertex and fragment shaders. They allow heavy calculations to be offloaded to the GPU with minimal overhead.

Note: This tutorial assumes familiarity with general shader concepts. Refer to the introduction to shaders and your first shader tutorials before proceeding.

Compute shaders are written directly in GLSL. To create a compute shader, create a new file (e.g., `compute_example.glsl`) in your project folder.

Note: Compute shaders are only supported by RenderingDevice-based renderers (Forward+ or Mobile). Ensure you are using one of these renderers. Support on mobile devices may be limited due to driver issues.

The following GLSL code defines a basic compute shader:

```glsl
#[compute]
#version 450

// Invocations in the (x, y, z) dimension
layout(local_size_x = 2, local_size_y = 1, local_size_z = 1) in;

// A binding to the buffer we create in our script
layout(set = 0, binding = 0, std430) restrict buffer MyDataBuffer {
    float data[];
}
my_data_buffer;

// The code we want to execute in each invocation
void main() {
    // gl_GlobalInvocationID.x uniquely identifies this invocation across all work groups
    my_data_buffer.data[gl_GlobalInvocationID.x] *= 2.0;
}
```

This shader takes an array of floats, multiplies each element by 2, and stores the result back into the buffer.

Line-by-line explanation:

`#[compute]`
`#version 450`
These lines indicate that the code is a compute shader and uses GLSL version 450. The `#[compute]` directive is a Godot-specific hint for proper file import. These lines typically do not need modification.

`layout(local_size_x = 2, local_size_y = 1, local_size_z = 1) in;`
This line defines the number of invocations per workgroup. Invocations are instances of the shader running within a workgroup, and workgroups run in parallel. This example uses 2 invocations per workgroup.

`layout(set = 0, binding = 0, std430) restrict buffer MyDataBuffer { float data[]; } my_data_buffer;`
This section declares the memory buffer accessible by the shader. The `layout` specifies the `set` and `binding` indices, which must match the CPU-side setup. The `restrict` keyword optimizes the shader by indicating the buffer is accessed from a single location. This is an unsized buffer, requiring careful index management.

`void main() { my_data_buffer.data[gl_GlobalInvocationID.x] *= 2.0; }`
The `main` function contains the core logic. `gl_GlobalInvocationID.x` provides a unique identifier for each invocation, used here to access and modify elements in the `my_data_buffer`.
